article.description:
Vince Carter had 20 points, seven assists, six rebounds and four blocks to lead the host Toronto Raptors to an 83-72
win over the Portland Trail Blazers on Sunday.
article.headline: All five Toronto starters score in double figures
article.linkText: Versatile Carter leads Raptors past Blazers
article.story:
TORONTO (AP) -- Vince Carter and the Toronto Raptors erased the memory of a poor game against the Los Angeles Clippers with a solid outing against Portland. Carter had 20 points, seven assists, six rebounds and four blocks to lead the Raptors to an 83-72 win over the Trail Blazers on Sunday. Jalen Rose had 17 points, and Donyell Marshall added 16 points and 11 rebounds for the Raptors, who rebounded from Friday's loss to the short-handed Clippers. In that game, Carter had just 12 points and Marshall scored just two. "The effort that we put out made us want to play better," Carter said. "We wanted to win. We weren't happy with our performance." All of Toronto's starters scored in double figures against Portland, and Carter set the tone by attacking the basket early. "I came to play from the beginning," Carter said. "I didn't play well on either end of the court last game. I was trying to be aggressive in putting the ball in the basket and finding open guys." Toronto coach Kevin O'Neill liked that Carter attacked the basket. "That's what we expect of Vince," O'Neill said. "I thought he did a great job of imposing his will on their defense and really making big-time plays." Jeff McInnis had 20 points for the Trail Blazers, who played their second straight game without Rasheed Wallace, sidelined with a sprained left ankle. McInnis thinks Portland has something in common with Toronto. "The Raptors have been struggling and we have been struggling with effort," McInnis said. "They are kind of like us, they don't play all the time, but they got guys on their team that can play and when they do play they are capable of beating anybody." The Raptors played their second consecutive without rookie center Chris Bosh, who is day to day with a strained right knee. Lonny Baxter, who had just one rebound in place of Bosh on Friday, had 10 points and six rebounds against the Trail Blazers. "We played very hard, very focused, very well right from the beginning and played a full 48 minutes," O'Neill said. The Trail Blazers couldn't say the same. Derek Anderson, who had a season-high 19 points in a win over Chicago on Friday, shot 0-for-10 from field and finished with two points. Zach Randolph scored 10 points on 5-for-17 shooting and had six rebounds for the Blazers, who have won just two of 16 road games. "It seems at times like we are just out there," Portland's Damon Stoudamire said. "There is really no explanation for the effort that we give sometimes. We tend to think teams are going to come out and roll over and die." Morris Peterson made an off-balance 3-pointer to extend Toronto's lead to 13 points in the third quarter. Rose made a turnaround jumper and Marshall scored on a fastbreak dunk to give Toronto a 16-point lead with 9:28 left. Carter's running jumper gave Toronto a 72-59 lead with 6:11 left, and Rose's three-point play made it 79-67 with 1:28 remaining. McInnis made two free throws to cut Toronto's lead to 10 with 1:25 left, but Alvin Williams countered with two jumpers. Toronto outscored Portland 21-12 in the second quarter as the Trail Blazers shot just 3-for-21 from the field. Portland tied a season-low with just 33 points in the first half. Toronto led by 10 at halftime.

Game notes
Wallace, injured in Thursday night's loss to Minnesota, is listed as day to day. He is averaging 16.8 points and 6.6 rebounds. ... The Raptors lost their previous four games to Portland. ... Toronto outscored Portland 32-24 in the paint.
